# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: metric-space-tree
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:metric-space-tree/ball-tree] In computer science, a **ball tree**, **balltree** or **metric tree**, is a space partitioning data structure for organizing points in a multi-dimensional space.
[src:metric-space-tree/ball-tree] A ball tree partitions data points into a nested set of balls.
[src:metric-space-tree/ball-tree] The resulting data structure has characteristics that make it useful for a number of applications, most notably nearest neighbor search.
[src:metric-space-tree/ball-tree] A ball tree is a binary tree in which every node defines a D-dimensional ball containing a subset of the points to be searched.
[src:metric-space-tree/ball-tree] Each internal node of the tree partitions the data points into two disjoint sets which are associated with different balls.
[src:metric-space-tree/ball-tree] While the balls themselves may intersect, each point is assigned to one or the other ball in the partition according to its distance from the ball's center.
[src:metric-space-tree/ball-tree] Each leaf node in the tree defines a ball and enumerates all data points inside that ball.
[src:metric-space-tree/ball-tree] Each node in the tree defines the smallest ball that contains all data points in its subtree.
[src:metric-space-tree/ball-tree] This gives rise to the useful property that, for a given test point t outside the ball, the distance to any point in a ball B in the tree is greater than or equal to the distance from t to the surface of the ball.
[src:metric-space-tree/ball-tree] Where $D^{B}(t)$ is the minimum possible distance from any point in the ball B to some point t.
[src:metric-space-tree/ball-tree] Ball-trees are related to the M-tree, but only support binary splits, whereas in the M-tree each level splits m to $2m$ fold, thus leading to a shallower tree structure, therefore need fewer distance computations, which usually yields faster queries.
[src:metric-space-tree/ball-tree] Furthermore, M-trees can better be stored on disk, which is organized in pages.
[src:metric-space-tree/ball-tree] The M-tree also keeps the distances from the parent node precomputed to speed up queries.
[src:metric-space-tree/ball-tree] Vantage-point trees are also similar, but they binary split into one ball, and the remaining data, instead of using two balls.
[src:metric-space-tree/ball-tree] A number of ball tree construction algorithms are available.
[src:metric-space-tree/ball-tree] The goal of such an algorithm is to produce a tree that will efficiently support queries of the desired type (e.g. nearest-neighbor) in the average case.
[src:metric-space-tree/ball-tree] The specific criteria of an ideal tree will depend on the type of question being answered and the distribution of the underlying data.
[src:metric-space-tree/ball-tree] However, a generally applicable measure of an efficient tree is one that minimizes the total volume of its internal nodes.
[src:metric-space-tree/ball-tree] Given the varied distributions of real-world data sets, this is a difficult task, but there are several heuristics that partition the data well in practice.
[src:metric-space-tree/ball-tree] In general, there is a tradeoff between the cost of constructing a tree and the efficiency achieved by this metric.
[src:metric-space-tree/ball-tree] This section briefly describes the simplest of these algorithms.
[src:metric-space-tree/ball-tree] A more in-depth discussion of five algorithms was given by Stephen Omohundro.
[src:metric-space-tree/ball-tree] The simplest such procedure is termed the "*k*-d Construction Algorithm", by analogy with the process used to construct *k*-d trees.
[src:metric-space-tree/ball-tree] This is an offline algorithm, that is, an algorithm that operates on the entire data set at once.
[src:metric-space-tree/ball-tree] The tree is built top-down by recursively splitting the data points into two sets.
[src:metric-space-tree/ball-tree] Splits are chosen along the single dimension with the greatest spread of points, with the sets partitioned by the median value of all points along that dimension.
[src:metric-space-tree/ball-tree] Finding the split for each internal node requires linear time in the number of samples contained in that node, yielding an algorithm with time complexity $O(n\,\log \,n)$ , where *n* is the number of data points.
[src:metric-space-tree/ball-tree] An important application of ball trees is expediting nearest neighbor search queries, in which the objective is to find the k points in the tree that are closest to a given test point by some distance metric (e.g.
[src:metric-space-tree/ball-tree] A simple search algorithm, sometimes called KNS1, exploits the distance property of the ball tree.
[src:metric-space-tree/ball-tree] In particular, if the algorithm is searching the data structure with a test point *t*, and has already seen some point *p* that is closest to *t* among the points encountered so far, then any subtree whose ball is further from *t* than *p* can be ignored for the rest of the search.
[src:metric-space-tree/ball-tree] The ball tree nearest-neighbor algorithm examines nodes in depth-first order, starting at the root.
[src:metric-space-tree/ball-tree] During the search, the algorithm maintains a max-first priority queue (often implemented with a heap), denoted *Q* here, of the k nearest points encountered so far.
[src:metric-space-tree/ball-tree] If *B* is a leaf node, scan through every point enumerated in *B* and update the nearest-neighbor queue appropriately.
[src:metric-space-tree/ball-tree] If *B* is an internal node, call the algorithm recursively on *B'*s two children, searching the child whose center is closer to *t* first.
[src:metric-space-tree/ball-tree] Return the queue after each of these calls has updated it in turn.
[src:metric-space-tree/ball-tree] Performing the recursive search in the order described in point 3 above increases likelihood that the further child will be pruned entirely during the search.
[src:metric-space-tree/ball-tree] In comparison with several other data structures, ball trees have been shown to perform fairly well on the nearest-neighbor search problem, particularly as their number of dimensions grows.
[src:metric-space-tree/ball-tree] However, the best nearest-neighbor data structure for a given application will depend on the dimensionality, number of data points, and underlying structure of the data.
[src:metric-space-tree/bk-tree] A **BK-tree** (short for **Burkhard-Keller tree**) is a metric tree suggested by Walter Austin Burkhard and Robert M.
[src:metric-space-tree/bk-tree] Keller specifically adapted to discrete metric spaces.
[src:metric-space-tree/bk-tree] For simplicity, given a way to measure the **distance** between any two elements of a set, a BK-tree is built with a single root node and several subtrees, each connected to the root as a child.
[src:metric-space-tree/bk-tree] All nodes in a subtree have an equal distance to the root node, and the edge weight of the edge connecting the subtree to the root is equal to the distance.
[src:metric-space-tree/bk-tree] Also, each subtree of a BK-tree is a BK-tree.
[src:metric-space-tree/bk-tree] BK-trees can be used for approximate string matching in a dictionary .
[src:metric-space-tree/bk-tree] The problem is formulated as follows: Given a pattern string $P=p_{1}p_{2}...p_{m}$ and a text string $T=t_{1}t_{2}\dots t_{n}$ , we need to find a substring $T_{j',j}=t_{j'}\dots t_{j}$ in T , which, of all substrings of T , has the smallest edit distance to the pattern P .
[src:metric-space-tree/bk-tree] An ordinary way using BK-tree is to insert all $\Theta (n^{2})$ substrings of T and the pattern string P into the BK-tree, and find the subtree containing nodes with the smallest distance from the root.
[src:metric-space-tree/bk-tree] This will lead to a time complexity of $\Theta (n^{2}\log n)$ .
[src:metric-space-tree/bk-tree] However, this algorithm is very accurate and can find every substrings with the smallest edit distance to P .
[src:metric-space-tree/bk-tree] The insertion primitive is used to populate a BK-tree t according to a discrete metric d .
[src:metric-space-tree/bk-tree] Given a searched element w , the lookup primitive traverses the BK-tree to find the closest element of w .
[src:metric-space-tree/bk-tree] The key idea is to restrict the exploration of t to nodes that can only improve the best candidate found so far by taking advantage of the BK-tree organization and of the triangle inequality (cut-off criterion).
[src:metric-space-tree/bk-tree] Consider the example 8-node B-K Tree shown above and set $w=$ "cool".
[src:metric-space-tree/bk-tree] S is initialized to contain the root of the tree, which is subsequently popped as the first value of u with $w_{u}$ ="book".
[src:metric-space-tree/bk-tree] Further $d_{u}=2$ since the distance from "book" to "cool" is 2, and $d_{best}=2$ as this is the best (i.e. smallest) distance found thus far.
[src:metric-space-tree/bk-tree] Next each outgoing arc from the root is considered in turn: the arc from "book" to "books" has weight 1, and since $|1-2|=1$ is less than $d_{best}=2$ , the node containing "books" is inserted into S for further processing.
[src:metric-space-tree/bk-tree] The next arc, from "book" to "cake," has weight 4, and since $|4-2|=2$ is not less than $d_{best}=2$ , the node containing "cake" is not inserted into S .
[src:metric-space-tree/bk-tree] Therefore, the subtree rooted at "cake" will be pruned from the search, as the word closest to "cool" cannot appear in that subtree.
[src:metric-space-tree/bk-tree] Therefore, it is safe to disregard the entire subtree rooted at "cake".
[src:metric-space-tree/bk-tree] Next the node containing "books" is popped from S and now $d_{u}=3$ , the distance from "cool" to "books." As $d_{u}>d_{best}$ , $d_{best}$ remains set at 2 and the single outgoing arc from the node containing "books" is considered.
[src:metric-space-tree/bk-tree] Next, the node containing "boo" is popped from S and $d_{u}=2$ , the distance from "cool" to "boo." This again does not improve upon $d_{best}=2$ .
[src:metric-space-tree/bk-tree] Each outgoing arc from "boo" is now considered; the arc from "boo" to "boon" has weight 1, and since $|2-1|=1<d_{best}=2$ , "boon" is added to S .
[src:metric-space-tree/bk-tree] Similarly, since $|2-2|=0<d_{best}$ , "cook" is also added to S .
[src:metric-space-tree/bk-tree] Finally each of the two last elements in S are considered in arbitrary order: suppose the node containing "cook" is popped first, improving $d_{best}$ to distance 1, then the node containing "boon" is popped last, which has distance 2 from "cool" and therefore does not improve the best result.
[src:metric-space-tree/bk-tree] Finally, "cook" is returned as the answer $w_{best}$ with $d_{best}=1$ .
[src:metric-space-tree/bk-tree] The efficiency of BK-trees depends strongly on the structure of the tree and the distribution of distances between stored elements.
[src:metric-space-tree/bk-tree] In the **average case**, both insertion and lookup operations take $\Theta (\log n)$ time, assuming the tree remains relatively balanced and the distance metric distributes elements evenly.
[src:metric-space-tree/bk-tree] In the **worst case**, when the data or distance function causes the tree to become highly unbalanced (for example, when many elements are at similar distances), both insertion and lookup can degrade to $\Theta (n)$ .
[src:metric-space-tree/bk-tree] In practical applications, the actual performance depends on the choice of distance metric (e.g., the Levenshtein distance) and on the allowed search radius during approximate matching.
[src:metric-space-tree/cover-tree] The **cover tree** is a type of data structure in computer science that is specifically designed to facilitate the speed-up of a nearest neighbor search.
[src:metric-space-tree/cover-tree] It is a refinement of the Navigating Net data structure, and related to a variety of other data structures developed for indexing intrinsically low-dimensional data.
[src:metric-space-tree/cover-tree] The tree can be thought of as a hierarchy of levels with the top level containing the root point and the bottom level containing every point in the metric space.
[src:metric-space-tree/cover-tree] Each level *C* is associated with an integer value *i* that decrements by one as the tree is descended.
[src:metric-space-tree/cover-tree] Like other metric trees the cover tree allows for nearest neighbor searches in $O(\eta *\log {n})$ where $\eta$ is a constant associated with the dimensionality of the dataset and n is the cardinality.
[src:metric-space-tree/cover-tree] To compare, a basic linear search requires $O(n)$ , which is a much worse dependence on n .
[src:metric-space-tree/cover-tree] However, in high-dimensional metric spaces the $\eta$ constant is non-trivial, which means it cannot be ignored in complexity analysis.
[src:metric-space-tree/cover-tree] Unlike other metric trees, the cover tree has a theoretical bound on its constant that is based on the dataset's expansion constant or doubling constant (in the case of approximate NN retrieval).
[src:metric-space-tree/cover-tree] The bound on search time is $O(c^{12}\log {n})$ where c is the expansion constant of the dataset.
[src:metric-space-tree/cover-tree] Although cover trees provide faster searches than the naive approach, this advantage must be weighed with the additional cost of maintaining the data structure.
[src:metric-space-tree/cover-tree] In a naive approach adding a new point to the dataset is trivial because order does not need to be preserved, but in a cover tree it can take $O(c^{6}\log {n})$ time.
[src:metric-space-tree/cover-tree] However, this is an upper-bound, and some techniques have been implemented that seem to improve the performance in practice.
[src:metric-space-tree/cover-tree] The cover tree uses implicit representation to keep track of repeated points.
[src:metric-space-tree/m-tree] In computer science, **M-trees** are tree data structures that are similar to R-trees and B-trees.
[src:metric-space-tree/m-tree] It is constructed using a metric and relies on the triangle inequality for efficient range and k-nearest neighbor (k-NN) queries.
[src:metric-space-tree/m-tree] While M-trees can perform well in many conditions, the tree can also have large overlap and there is no clear strategy on how to best avoid overlap.
[src:metric-space-tree/m-tree] In addition, it can only be used for distance functions that satisfy the triangle inequality, while many advanced dissimilarity functions used in information retrieval do not satisfy this.
[src:metric-space-tree/m-tree] As in any tree-based data structure, the M-tree is composed of nodes and leaves.
[src:metric-space-tree/m-tree] In each node there is a data object that identifies it uniquely and a pointer to a sub-tree where its children reside.
[src:metric-space-tree/m-tree] For each node there is a radius r that defines a Ball in the desired metric space.
[src:metric-space-tree/m-tree] Thus, every node n and leaf l residing in a particular node N is at most distance r from N , and every node n and leaf l with node parent N keep the distance from it.
[src:metric-space-tree/m-tree] The main idea is first to find a leaf node N where the new object O belongs.
[src:metric-space-tree/m-tree] If N is not full then just attach it to N.
[src:metric-space-tree/m-tree] If N is full then invoke a method to split N.
[src:metric-space-tree/m-tree] If the split method arrives to the root of the tree, then it choose two routing objects from N, and creates two new nodes containing all the objects in original N, and store them into the new root.
[src:metric-space-tree/m-tree] If split methods arrives to a node N that is not the root of the tree, the method choose two new routing objects from N, re-arrange every routing object in N in two new nodes $N_{1}$ and $N_{2}$ , and store these new nodes in the parent node $N_{p}$ of original N.
[src:metric-space-tree/m-tree] The split must be repeated if $N_{p}$ has not enough capacity to store $N_{2}$ .
[src:metric-space-tree/m-tree] A range query is where a minimum similarity/maximum distance value is specified.
[src:metric-space-tree/m-tree] For a given query object ⁠ $Q\in D$ ⁠ and a maximum search distance ⁠ $r(Q)$ ⁠, the range query **range**(Q, r(Q)) selects all the indexed objects ⁠ $O_{j}$ ⁠ such that ⁠ $d(O_{j},Q)\leq r(Q)$ ⁠.
[src:metric-space-tree/m-tree] Algorithm RangeSearch starts from the root node and recursively traverses all the paths which cannot be excluded from leading to qualifying objects.
[src:metric-space-tree/metric-tree] A **metric tree** is any tree data structure specialized to index data in metric spaces.
[src:metric-space-tree/metric-tree] Metric trees exploit properties of metric spaces such as the triangle inequality to make accesses to the data more efficient.
[src:metric-space-tree/metric-tree] Examples include the M-tree, vp-trees, cover trees, MVP trees, and BK-trees.
[src:metric-space-tree/metric-tree] These data structures are well-suited for range query problems asking for every point $(x,y)$ that satisfies ${\mbox{min}}_{x}\leq x\leq {\mbox{max}}_{x}$ and ${\mbox{min}}_{y}\leq y\leq {\mbox{max}}_{y}$ .
[src:metric-space-tree/metric-tree] A limitation of these multidimensional search structures is that they are only defined for searching over objects that can be treated as vectors.
[src:metric-space-tree/metric-tree] They are not applicable for the more general case in which the algorithm is given only a collection of objects and a function for measuring the distance or similarity between two objects.
[src:metric-space-tree/metric-tree] If, for example, someone were to create a function that returns a value indicating how similar one image is to another, a natural algorithmic problem would be to take a dataset of images and find the ones that are similar according to the function to a given query image.
[src:metric-space-tree/metric-tree] If there is no structure to the similarity measure then a brute force search requiring the comparison of the query image to every image in the dataset is the best that can be done .
[src:metric-space-tree/metric-tree] If, however, the similarity function satisfies the triangle inequality then it is possible to use the result of each comparison to prune the set of candidates to be examined.
[src:metric-space-tree/metric-tree] The first article on metric trees, as well as the first use of the term "metric tree", published in the open literature was by Jeffrey Uhlmann in 1991.
[src:metric-space-tree/metric-tree] Other researchers were working independently on similar data structures.
[src:metric-space-tree/metric-tree] In particular, Peter Yianilos claimed to have independently discovered the same method, which he called a vantage point tree (VP-tree).
[src:metric-space-tree/metric-tree] The research on metric tree data structures blossomed in the late 1990s and included an examination by Google co-founder Sergey Brin of their use for very large databases.
[src:metric-space-tree/metric-tree] The first textbook on metric data structures was published in 2006.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Formally, the nearest neighbor (NN) search problem is defined as follows: given a set S of points in a space M and a query point $q\in M$ , find the closest point in S to q.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Donald Knuth in volume 3 of *The Art of Computer Programming* (1973) called it the **post-office problem**, referring to an application of assigning to a residence the nearest post office.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] A direct generalization of this problem is a k-NN search, where we need to find the k closest points.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Most commonly M is a metric space and dissimilarity is expressed as a distance metric, which is symmetric and satisfies the triangle inequality.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Even more common, M is taken to be the d-dimensional vector space where dissimilarity is measured using the Euclidean distance, Manhattan distance or other distance metric.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] However, the dissimilarity function can be arbitrary.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] One example is asymmetric Bregman divergence, for which the triangle inequality does not hold.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Various solutions to the NNS problem have been proposed.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] The quality and usefulness of the algorithms are determined by the time complexity of queries as well as the space complexity of any search data structures that must be maintained.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] The informal observation usually referred to as the curse of dimensionality states that there is no general-purpose exact solution for NNS in high-dimensional Euclidean space using polynomial preprocessing and polylogarithmic search time.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] The simplest solution to the NNS problem is to compute the distance from the query point to every other point in the database, keeping track of the "best so far".
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] This algorithm, sometimes referred to as the naive approach, has a running time of *O*(*dN*), where *N* is the cardinality of *S* and *d* is the dimensionality of *S*.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] There are no search data structures to maintain, so the linear search has no space complexity beyond the storage of the database.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Naive search can, on average, outperform space partitioning approaches on higher dimensional spaces.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] The absolute distance is not required for distance comparison, only the relative distance.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] In geometric coordinate systems the distance calculation can be sped up considerably by omitting the square root calculation from the distance calculation between two coordinates.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] The distance comparison will still yield identical results.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Since the 1970s, the branch and bound methodology has been applied to the problem.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] In the case of Euclidean space, this approach encompasses spatial index or spatial access methods.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Several space-partitioning methods have been developed for solving the NNS problem.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Perhaps the simplest is the k-d tree, which iteratively bisects the search space into two regions containing half of the points of the parent region.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Queries are performed via traversal of the tree from the root to a leaf by evaluating the query point at each split.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Depending on the distance specified in the query, neighboring branches that might contain hits may also need to be evaluated.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] R-trees can yield nearest neighbors not only for Euclidean distance, but can also be used with other distances.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] In the case of general metric space, the branch-and-bound approach is known as the metric tree approach.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Particular examples include vp-tree and BK-tree methods.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Using a set of points taken from a 3-dimensional space and put into a BSP tree, and given a query point taken from the same space, a possible solution to the problem of finding the nearest point-cloud point to the query point is given in the following description of an algorithm.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] (Strictly speaking, no such point may exist, because it may not be unique.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] This may not be the case, but it is a good heuristic.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] After having recursively gone through all the trouble of solving the problem for the guessed half-space, now compare the distance returned by this result with the shortest distance from the query point to the partitioning plane.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] This latter distance is that between the query point and the closest possible point that could exist in the half-space not searched.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] If this distance is greater than that returned in the earlier result, then clearly there is no need to search the other half-space.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] If there is such a need, then you must go through the trouble of solving the problem for the other half space, and then compare its result to the former result, and then return the proper result.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] An approximate nearest neighbor search algorithm is allowed to return points whose distance from the query is at most c times the distance from the query to its nearest points.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] The appeal of this approach is that, in many cases, an approximate nearest neighbor is almost as good as the exact one.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] In particular, if the distance measure accurately captures the notion of user quality, then small differences in the distance should not matter.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Proximity graph methods (such as navigable small world graphs and HNSW) are considered the current state-of-the-art for the approximate nearest neighbors search.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] The methods are based on greedy traversing in proximity neighborhood graphs $G(V,E)$ in which every point $x_{i}\in S$ is uniquely associated with vertex $v_{i}\in V$ .
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] The search for the nearest neighbors to a query *q* in the set *S* takes the form of searching for the vertex in the graph $G(V,E)$ .
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] The basic algorithm – greedy search – works as follows: search starts from an enter-point vertex $v_{i}\in V$ by computing the distances from the query q to each vertex of its neighborhood $\{v_{j}:(v_{i},v_{j})\in E\}$ , and then finds a vertex with the minimal distance value.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] If the distance value between the query and the selected vertex is smaller than the one between the query and the current element, then the algorithm moves to the selected vertex, and it becomes new enter-point.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] The algorithm stops when it reaches a local minimum: a vertex whose neighborhood does not contain a vertex that is closer to the query than the vertex itself.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] These works were preceded by a pioneering paper by Toussaint, in which he introduced the concept of a *relative neighborhood* graph.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Locality sensitive hashing (LSH) is a technique for grouping points in space into 'buckets' based on some distance metric operating on the points.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Points that are close to each other under the chosen metric are mapped to the same bucket with high probability.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] The cover tree has a theoretical bound that is based on the dataset's doubling constant.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] The bound on search time is *O*(*c*12 log *n*) where *c* is the expansion constant of the dataset.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] In the special case where the data is a dense 3D map of geometric points, the projection geometry of the sensing technique can be used to dramatically simplify the search problem.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] This approach requires that the 3D data is organized by a projection to a two-dimensional grid and assumes that the data is spatially smooth across neighboring grid cells with the exception of object boundaries.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] These assumptions are valid when dealing with 3D sensor data in applications such as surveying, robotics and stereo vision but may not hold for unorganized data in general.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] In practice this technique has an average search time of *O*(*1*) or *O*(*K*) for the *k*-nearest neighbor problem when applied to real world stereo vision data.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] In high-dimensional spaces, tree indexing structures become useless because an increasing percentage of the nodes need to be examined anyway.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] To speed up linear search, a compressed version of the feature vectors stored in RAM is used to prefilter the datasets in a first run.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] The final candidates are determined in a second stage using the uncompressed data from the disk for distance calculation.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] The VA-file approach is a special case of a compression based search, where each feature component is compressed uniformly and independently.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] The optimal compression technique in multidimensional spaces is Vector Quantization (VQ), implemented through clustering.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] The database is clustered and the most "promising" clusters are retrieved.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Huge gains over VA-File, tree-based indexes and sequential scan have been observed.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Also note the parallels between clustering and LSH.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] There are numerous variants of the NNS problem and the two most well-known are the *k*-nearest neighbor search and the ε-approximate nearest neighbor search.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] In some applications it may be acceptable to retrieve a "good guess" of the nearest neighbor.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] In those cases, we can use an algorithm which doesn't guarantee to return the actual nearest neighbor in every case, in return for improved speed or memory savings.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Often such an algorithm will find the nearest neighbor in a majority of cases, but this depends strongly on the dataset being queried.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Algorithms that support the approximate nearest neighbor search include locality-sensitive hashing, best bin first and balanced box-decomposition tree based search.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Nearest neighbor distance ratio does not apply the threshold on the direct distance from the original point to the challenger neighbor but on a ratio of it depending on the distance to the previous neighbor.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] It is used in CBIR to retrieve pictures through a "query by example" using the similarity between local features.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] More generally it is involved in several matching problems.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Fixed-radius near neighbors is the problem where one wants to efficiently find all points given in Euclidean space within a given fixed distance from a specified point.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] The distance is assumed to be fixed, but the query point is arbitrary.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] For some applications (e.g. entropy estimation), we may have *N* data-points and wish to know which is the nearest neighbor *for every one of those N points*.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] This could, of course, be achieved by running a nearest-neighbor search once for every point, but an improved strategy would be an algorithm that exploits the information redundancy between these *N* queries to produce a more efficient search.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] As a simple example: when we find the distance from point *X* to point *Y*, that also tells us the distance from point *Y* to point *X*, so the same calculation can be reused in two different queries.
[src:metric-space-tree/nearest-neighbor-search] Given a fixed dimension, a semi-definite positive norm (thereby including every Lp norm), and *n* points in this space, the nearest neighbour of every point can be found in *O*(*n* log *n*) time and the *m* nearest neighbours of every point can be found in *O*(*mn* log *n*) time.
[src:metric-space-tree/vantage-point-tree] By recursively applying this procedure to partition the data into smaller and smaller sets, a tree data structure is created where neighbors in the tree are likely to be neighbors in the space.
[src:metric-space-tree/vantage-point-tree] One generalization is called a **multi-vantage-point tree** (or **MVP tree**): a data structure for indexing objects from large metric spaces for similarity search queries.
[src:metric-space-tree/vantage-point-tree] It uses more than one point to partition each level.
[src:metric-space-tree/vantage-point-tree] Peter Yianilos claimed that the vantage-point tree was discovered independently by him (Peter Yianilos) and by Jeffrey Uhlmann.
[src:metric-space-tree/vantage-point-tree] Yet, Uhlmann published this method before Yianilos in 1991.
[src:metric-space-tree/vantage-point-tree] Uhlmann called the data structure a metric tree, the name VP-tree was proposed by Yianilos.
[src:metric-space-tree/vantage-point-tree] Vantage-point trees have been generalized to non-metric spaces using Bregman divergence by Nielsen et al.
[src:metric-space-tree/vantage-point-tree] This iterative partitioning process is similar to that of a *k*-d tree, but uses circular (or spherical, hyperspherical, etc.) rather than rectilinear partitions.
[src:metric-space-tree/vantage-point-tree] In two-dimensional Euclidean space, this can be visualized as a series of circles segregating the data.
[src:metric-space-tree/vantage-point-tree] The vantage-point tree is particularly useful in dividing data in a non-standard metric space into a metric tree.
[src:metric-space-tree/vantage-point-tree] The way a vantage-point tree stores data can be represented by a circle.
[src:metric-space-tree/vantage-point-tree] First, understand that each node of this tree contains an input point and a radius.
[src:metric-space-tree/vantage-point-tree] All the left children of a given node are the points inside the circle and all the right children of a given node are outside of the circle.
[src:metric-space-tree/vantage-point-tree] The tree itself does not need to know any other information about what is being stored.
[src:metric-space-tree/vantage-point-tree] All it needs is the distance function that satisfies the properties of the metric space.
[src:metric-space-tree/vantage-point-tree] A vantage-point tree can be used to find the nearest neighbor of a point *x*.
[src:metric-space-tree/vantage-point-tree] At any given step we are working with a node of the tree that has a vantage point *v* and a threshold distance *t*.
[src:metric-space-tree/vantage-point-tree] The point of interest *x* will be some distance from the vantage point *v*.
[src:metric-space-tree/vantage-point-tree] If the recursive use of the algorithm finds a neighboring point *n* with distance to *x* that is less than |*t* − *d*| then it cannot help to search the other subtree of this node; the discovered node *n* is returned.
[src:metric-space-tree/vantage-point-tree] Otherwise, the other subtree also needs to be searched recursively.
[src:metric-space-tree/vantage-point-tree] A similar approach works for finding the *k* nearest neighbors of a point *x*.
[src:metric-space-tree/vantage-point-tree] In the recursion, the other subtree is searched for *k* − *k′* nearest neighbors of the point *x* whenever only *k′* (< *k*) of the nearest neighbors found so far have distance that is less than |*t* − *d*|.
[src:metric-space-tree/vantage-point-tree] Updating a vantage-point tree is relatively easy compared to the FastMap approach.
[src:metric-space-tree/vantage-point-tree] For FastMap, after inserting or deleting data, there will come a time when FastMap will have to rescan itself.
[src:metric-space-tree/vantage-point-tree] That takes up too much time and it is unclear to know when the rescanning will start.
[src:metric-space-tree/vantage-point-tree] The time cost to build a vantage-point tree is approximately *O*(*n* log *n*).
[src:metric-space-tree/vantage-point-tree] For each element, the tree is descended by log *n* levels to find its placement.
[src:metric-space-tree/vantage-point-tree] However there is a constant factor *k* where *k* is the number of vantage points per tree node.
[src:metric-space-tree/vantage-point-tree] The time cost to search a vantage-point tree to find a single nearest neighbor is *O*(log *n*).
[src:metric-space-tree/vantage-point-tree] There are log *n* levels, each involving *k* distance calculations, where *k* is the number of vantage points (elements) at that position in the tree.
[src:metric-space-tree/vantage-point-tree] The time cost to search a vantage-point tree for a range, which may be the most important attribute, can vary greatly depending on the specifics of the algorithm used and parameters.
[src:metric-space-tree/vantage-point-tree] Brin's paper gives the result of experiments with several vantage point algorithms with various parameters to investigate the cost, measured in number of distance calculations.
[src:metric-space-tree/vantage-point-tree] The space cost for a vantage-point tree is approximately *n*.
[src:metric-space-tree/vantage-point-tree] Each element is stored, and each tree element in each non-leaf node requires a pointer to its descendant nodes.
[src:metric-space-tree/vantage-point-tree] (See Brin for details on one implementation choice.
[src:metric-space-tree/vantage-point-tree] With n points there are *O*(*n*2) pairwise distances between points.
[src:metric-space-tree/vantage-point-tree] However, the creation of a vantage-point tree requires that only *O*(*n* log *n*) distances be calculated explicitly, and a search requires only *O*(log *n*) distance calculations.
[src:metric-space-tree/vantage-point-tree] For example, if x and y are points and it is known that the distance *d*(*x*, *y*) is small then any point z that is far from x will also necessarily be almost as far from y because the metric space's triangle inequality gives *d*(*y*, *z*) ≥ *d*(*x*, *z*) − *d*(*x*, *y*).
